\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, we describe the setting in which the theoretical results
 of this thesis are stated, and review the existing theory upon which the
 original results presented in the following chapters will build.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Objects and Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first fix the main objects of study and notation.
 We will work on the probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{B}\left(\Omega\right),\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

, where the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathcal{C}\left(\left[0,1\right],\mathcal{R}^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the space of real-valued continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega:\left[0,1\right]\rightarrow\mathcal{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, which is equipped with its Borel 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 is a probability measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{B}\left(\Omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The canonical process 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left\{ X_{t}\right\} _{t\in\left[0,1\right]}$
\end_inset

 is defined to be such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{t}\left(\omega\right)\coloneqq\omega\left(t\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 For any subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\subseteq\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathcal{T}}=\left\{ X_{t}\right\} _{t\in\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 be the canonical process at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 be the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}\coloneqq\left\{ X_{t}\left(\omega\right):t\in\mathcal{T},\omega\in\Omega\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, for ease of notation, let 
\begin_inset Formula $t:u$
\end_inset

 be the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t,u\right]$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t,t+1,\dots,u-1,u\}$
\end_inset

, to be made clear by context.
 In general, we will take the density of a given measure to refer to its
 density with respect to the Lebesgue measure unless otherwise noted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following chapters, we will study in detail time-homogenous univariate
 Itô diffusions i.e.
 continuous and strongly Markovian diffusion processes (see standard references
 like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "Chapter 5 in"
key "oksendal"

\end_inset

 for details).
 In particular, we will study processes 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{t}-X_{0}=\int_{0}^{t}\mu(X_{s})ds+\int_{0}^{t}\sigma(X_{s})dW_{s},
\]

\end_inset

for a vector of independent Wiener processes 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 where the second integral is one in the sense of Itô.
 As per convention, we will refer to such processes as solutions to the
 stochastic differential equation (SDE)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dX_{t}=\mu(X_{t})dt+\sigma(X_{t})dW_{t},
\]

\end_inset

with a given initial condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In all diffusions to be studied, we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 are suitably regular, admitting a weakly unique solution (i.e.
 all solutions have the same finite-dimensional distributions), and finite
 speed measure.
 Note, for example, that the latter assumption excludes the Wiener process.
 Finally, we assume that any one dimesional diffusion considered satisfies
 the balance condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{t}(x,y)m(x)=p_{t}(y,x)m(y),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 are the transition density and density of the speed measure associated
 with the diffusion.
 We refer the reader to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "pp. 5-6 in"
key "bladt-sorensen-2014"

\end_inset

 for a detailed discussion of these conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote probability measures by capital letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P},\mathbb{Q},\dots$
\end_inset

 in blackboard boldface.
 Random variables will be denoted by capital letters 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y,\dots$
\end_inset

, and particular realizations by lower-case letters 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,\dots$
\end_inset

 as per convention.
 Vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\dots,$
\end_inset

 will be denoted in boldface, and note that a vector may also be a random
 variable.
 Subscripts will used to index by time i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the value of the stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 for some set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\subseteq[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Often, we will suppress set braces in subscripts for clarity, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0,1}$
\end_inset

 will denote the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}^{(i)}$
\end_inset

 will denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th element of vectors of countable length to avoid the overloading of the
 subscript operator.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 be the set of real numbers.
 Having set our notation, we now review some existing theory related to
 stochastic bridges which will form the foundation of the novel theoretical
 results to be presented in the following chapters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Markov and Generalized Bridges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we introduce the notion of a Markov bridge, pointing the
 reader towards references like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "Section 1 in"
key "leonard-2014"

\end_inset

 for an in-depth exposition of the subject.
 Then, we will summarize the relevant results of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "baudoin-2002"

\end_inset

 with respect to generalized bridge measures, objects which will feature
 heavily in the chapters to follow.
 None of the theory discussed in this section is original to this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we briefly study the well-known properties of Markov bridges.
 Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 as a Markov measure.
 Under fairly general conditions, like those laid out in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "Proposition 4 in"
key "fitz-pitman-1993"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 can be disintegrated as a mixture of regular conditional measures, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}=\int_{\mathcal{R}^{2}}\mathbb{P}(\cdot\mid X_{0}=x,X_{1}=y)\mathbb{P}_{0,1}(dxdy),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(\cdot\mid X_{0}=x,X_{1}=y)$
\end_inset

 exists for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in the state space and can be constructed using Doob's method of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-transforms (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "Section 45 in"
key "rogers"

\end_inset

 for a treatment of Doob's 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-transform in the case of diffusion processes).
 We refer to such a measure as the bridge measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the canonical process on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 can be understood as the canonical process on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

, with its endpoints pinned to certain values at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 can be understood as the mixture of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the mixing measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{0,1}$
\end_inset

.
 It can be easily shown that bridge measures inherit the Markov property
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 is also a Markov measure; furthermore, if certain densities of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 exist, then the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 at some time 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 also exists, as detailed in the below proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "Theorem 1.9 in"
key "leonard-2014"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:density-of-bridge"

\end_inset

For all 
\begin_inset Formula $0<t<1$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in the state space, the bridge measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{t}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

, is dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The density of the marginal bridge measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\mathbb{P}_{t}^{x,y}}{d\mathbb{P}_{t}}=\frac{p_{t}^{*}(x,\cdot)p_{1-t}(\cdot,y)}{c(x,y)},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}(x,y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}^{*}(x,y)$
\end_inset

 are the forward and backward transition densities of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{0,1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of a bridge measure has been expanded upon significantly in the
 literature (see, for instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "alili-2002,baudoin-coutin-2007"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sottinen-yazigi-2014"

\end_inset

).
 A generalization of particular interest to this thesis was first proposed
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "baudoin-2002"

\end_inset

; rather than conditioning a process on the value of its endpoints, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "baudoin-2002"

\end_inset

 formalizes the sense in which arbitrary functionals of a process can be
 conditioned on their law.
 We consolidate and present some of the major results of Baudoin below,
 working on the usual probability space.
 First, we define a Baudoin conditioning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
